{"title_page": "Herb McMath", "text_new": "{{Infobox gridiron football person\n| name = Herb McMath\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1954|9|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Coahoma, Mississippi]], United States\n| death_date = {{Death date|2016|10|5}}\n| death_place = Springfield, Illinois\n| team = \n| number = \n| status = \n| position1 = \n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 4\n| weight_lb = 248\n| high_school = [[Springfield Southeast High School]]\n| college = [[Morningside College|Morningside]]\n| NFLDraftedYear = 1976\n| NFLDraftedRound = 4\n| NFLDraftedPick = 110\n| NFLDraftedTeam = \n| playing_years1 = 1976\n| playing_team1 = [[Oakland Raiders]]\n| playing_years2 = 1977\n| playing_team2 = [[Green Bay Packers]]\n| career_highlights = \n}}\n'''Herbert Louis McMath, Sr. ''' (born September 6, 1954 in [[Coahoma, Mississippi]]) is a former American football [[defensive tackle]] and [[defensive End]] in the [[National Football League|NFL]] for the [[Oakland Raiders]] and the [[Green Bay Packers]].  He played 22 games in two seasons in the NFL and was a part of the Oakland Raiders 1976 Super Bowl Champion team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/McMaHe20.htm |title=Herb McMath NFL Football Statistics |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |date=1954-09-06 |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Super Bowl XI}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McMath, Herb}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Morningside Mustangs football players]]\n[[Category:Oakland Raiders players]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n[[Category:People from Coahoma, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Mississippi]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox gridiron football person\n| name = Herb McMath\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1954|9|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Coahoma, Mississippi]], United States\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2016|10|5}}\n| death_place = Springfield, Illinois\n| team = \n| number = \n| status = \n| position1 = \n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 4\n| weight_lb = 248\n| high_school = [[Springfield Southeast High School]]\n| college = [[Morningside College|Morningside]]\n| NFLDraftedYear = 1976\n| NFLDraftedRound = 4\n| NFLDraftedPick = 110\n| NFLDraftedTeam = \n| playing_years1 = 1976\n| playing_team1 = [[Oakland Raiders]]\n| playing_years2 = 1977\n| playing_team2 = [[Green Bay Packers]]\n| career_highlights = \n}}\n'''Herbert Louis McMath, Sr. ''' (born September 6, 1954 in [[Coahoma, Mississippi]]) is a former American football [[defensive tackle]] and [[defensive End]] in the [[National Football League|NFL]] for the [[Oakland Raiders]] and the [[Green Bay Packers]].  He played 22 games in two seasons in the NFL and was a part of the Oakland Raiders 1976 Super Bowl Champion team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/M/McMaHe20.htm |title=Herb McMath NFL Football Statistics |publisher=Pro-Football-Reference.com |date=1954-09-06 |accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Super Bowl XI}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McMath, Herb}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Morningside Mustangs football players]]\n[[Category:Oakland Raiders players]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n[[Category:People from Coahoma, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Mississippi]]\n", "name_user": "Jtayl132", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herb_McMath"}
{"title_page": "John MacDonald (Australian politician)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|text=[[John McDonald (Western Australian politician)]], a member of the Western Australian Legislative Assembly}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = John MacDonald\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = John Valentine MacDonald.jpg\n| title = [[Australian Senate|Senator]] for [[Queensland]]\n| term_start = 26 May 1922\n| term_end = 15 December 1922\n| predecessor = [[John Adamson (Queensland politician)|John Adamson]]\n| successor = [[William Thompson (Australian politician)|William Thompson]]\n| term_start1 = 1 August 1928\n| term_end1 = 16 November 1928\n| predecessor1 = [[Thomas Givens]]\n| term_start2 = 1 July 1932\n| term_end2 = 17 August 1937\n| successor2 = [[Ben Courtice]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1880|2|14}}\n| birth_place = [[Opotiki]], [[New Zealand]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1937|8|17|1880|2|14}}\n| death_place = [[New Farm, Queensland|New Farm]], [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]], Australia\n| nationality = [[Australian]]\n| spouse = \n| party = [[Australian Labor Party]]\n| relations = \n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = Journalist\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website = \n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''John Valentine (Jack) MacDonald''' (14 February 1880 &ndash; 17 August 1937) was a [[New Zealand]]-born [[Australia]]n politician.\n\nMacDonald was born in [[Opotiki]], [[New Zealand]], the son of an Australian volunteer in the [[New Zealand Wars]] and veteran of the [[1891 Australian shearers' strike]]. He completed his early education in New Zealand before his family migrated to New South Wales, whereafter he attended state schools. He spent time as a shearer in New South Wales and Victoria before returning to New Zealand and entering the printing trade. He began as a journeyman compositor, but shifted into journalism over time, working for the ''Wairoa Guardian'' and the [[Napier, New Zealand|Napier]]-based ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Napier, New Zealand)|The Daily Telegraph]]'' before rising to become chief compositor and acting editor of the ''[[Gisborne Herald]]''. He was also involved in the Typographical Association in its early days and taught shorthand at the Gisborne Technical College in 1903\u201304.<ref name=worker>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71270513 |title=SENATOR J.V. MacDONALD PASSES |newspaper=[[Worker]] |volume=48 |issue=2616 |location=Queensland, Australia |date=24 August 1937 |accessdate=1 September 2019 |page=13 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54634110 |title=NEW SENATOR. |newspaper=[[Morning Bulletin]] |issue=19,987 |location=Queensland, Australia |date=21 August 1928 |accessdate=1 September 2019 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref name=bulletin>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54634110 |title=NEW SENATOR. |newspaper=[[Morning Bulletin]] |issue=19,987 |location=Queensland, Australia |date=21 August 1928 |accessdate=1 September 2019 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article30768929 |title=Death Of Senator J. V. MacDonald |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |location=South Australia |date=18 August 1937 |accessdate=1 September 2019 |page=22 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article184241485 |title=LABOR'S TEAM IN QUEENSLAND, The Men Who Claim Your Votes. |newspaper=[[Daily Standard]] |issue=3093 |location=Queensland, Australia |date=2 December 1922 |accessdate=1 September 2019 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref>\n\nMacDonald later returned to Australia and worked as a journalist at ''[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]]'' and then ''[[The Age]]'' in [[Melbourne]], including a stint in the [[Canberra Press Gallery|parliamentary press gallery]]. He was one of the founding members of the [[Australian Journalists Association]] in 1910, spent time in [[London]] and studied at the [[University of London]], before returning to Australia. He was then recruited as editor of the new [[Brisbane]] newspaper ''[[The Daily Standard (Brisbane)|The Daily Standard]]'' in 1912, serving in that role until his appointment to the Senate and also serving as acting manager in 1913\u201314. He was involved in campaigning against the conscription referendums of [[Billy Hughes]], but in 1918 was one of 12 newspaper editors selected by the [[Nationalist Party (Australia)|Nationalist Party]] government to visit the [[World War I]] front.<ref name=worker /><ref name=bulletin />\n\nOn 26 May 1922, he was appointed to the [[Australian Senate]] as a [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] Senator for Queensland, filling the casual vacancy caused by the death of [[Nationalist Party of Australia|Nationalist]] Senator [[John Adamson (Queensland politician)|John Adamson]]; he had already been preselected as a Labor candidate for the forthcoming election. However, he was defeated at the [[1922 Australian federal election|1922 election]]. MacDonald worked as a freelance journalist in the intervening years. Following the death of another Nationalist Senator, [[Thomas Givens]], MacDonald was again appointed to the Senate on 1 August 1928 but was defeated again at the [[1928 Australian federal election|1928 election]]. He then worked as chief compiler for the Queensland Tourist Bureau, promoting the state's tourist opportunities. MacDonald was finally elected in his own right in the [[1931 Australian federal election|election of 1931]], taking his place in the Senate in 1932. He died in office in 1937 after suffering reported \"heart trouble\" and was cremated at [[Mount Thompson Crematorium]].<ref name=\"Psephos\">{{cite web|last=Carr |first=Adam |title=Australian Election Archive |work=Psephos, Adam Carr's Election Archive |url=http://psephos.adam-carr.net/countries/a/australia |year=2008 |accessdate=2008-11-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5QSilacl0?url=http://psephos.adam-carr.net/countries/a/australia |archivedate=20 July 2007 }}</ref><ref name=worker /><ref name=bulletin /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article70640723 |title=SENATOR J. V. MacDONALD DEAD |newspaper=[[The Central Queensland Herald]] |volume=9 |issue=400 |location=Queensland, Australia |date=19 August 1937 |accessdate=1 September 2019 |page=26 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article178928792 |title=J. V. MacDonald. |newspaper=[[Daily Standard]] |issue=5928 |location=Queensland, Australia |date=15 January 1932 |accessdate=1 September 2019 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Australia-Labor-senator-stub}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macdonald, John}}\n[[Category:Australian Labor Party members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate for Queensland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate]]\n[[Category:1880 births]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|text=[[John McDonald (Western Australian politician)]], a member of the Western Australian Legislative Assembly}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = John MacDonald\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = John Valentine MacDonald.jpg\n| title = [[Australian Senate|Senator]] for [[Queensland]]\n| term_start = 26 May 1922\n| term_end = 15 December 1922\n| predecessor = [[John Adamson (Queensland politician)|John Adamson]]\n| successor = [[William Thompson (Australian politician)|William Thompson]]\n| term_start1 = 1 August 1928\n| term_end1 = 16 November 1928\n| predecessor1 = [[Thomas Givens]]\n| term_start2 = 1 July 1932\n| term_end2 = 17 August 1937\n| successor2 = [[Ben Courtice]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1880|2|14}}\n| birth_place = [[Opotiki]], [[New Zealand]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1937|8|17|1880|2|14}}\n| death_place = [[New Farm, Queensland|New Farm]], [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]], Australia\n| nationality = [[Australian]]\n| spouse = \n| party = [[Australian Labor Party]]\n| relations = \n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = Journalist\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website = \n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''John Valentine (Jack) MacDonald''' (14 February 1880 &ndash; 17 August 1937) was a [[New Zealand]]-born [[Australia]]n politician.\n\nMacDonald was born in [[Opotiki]], [[New Zealand]], the son of an Australian volunteer in the [[New Zealand Wars]] and veteran of the [[1891 Australian shearers' strike]]. He completed his early education in New Zealand before his family migrated to New South Wales, whereafter he attended state schools. He spent time as a shearer in New South Wales and Victoria before returning to New Zealand and entering the printing trade. He began as a journeyman compositor, but shifted into journalism over time, working for the ''Wairoa Guardian'' and the [[Napier, New Zealand|Napier]]-based ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Napier, New Zealand)|The Daily Telegraph]]'' before rising to become chief compositor and acting editor of the ''[[Gisborne Herald]]''. He was also involved in the Typographical Association in its early days and taught shorthand at the Gisborne Technical College in 1903-04.<ref name=worker>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71270513 |title=SENATOR J.V. MacDONALD PASSES |newspaper=[[Worker]] |volume=48 |issue=2616 |location=Queensland, Australia |date=24 August 1937 |accessdate=1 September 2019 |page=13 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54634110 |title=NEW SENATOR. |newspaper=[[Morning Bulletin]] |issue=19,987 |location=Queensland, Australia |date=21 August 1928 |accessdate=1 September 2019 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref name=bulletin>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54634110 |title=NEW SENATOR. |newspaper=[[Morning Bulletin]] |issue=19,987 |location=Queensland, Australia |date=21 August 1928 |accessdate=1 September 2019 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article30768929 |title=Death Of Senator J. V. MacDonald |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)]] |location=South Australia |date=18 August 1937 |accessdate=1 September 2019 |page=22 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article184241485 |title=LABOR'S TEAM IN QUEENSLAND, The Men Who Claim Your Votes. |newspaper=[[Daily Standard]] |issue=3093 |location=Queensland, Australia |date=2 December 1922 |accessdate=1 September 2019 |page=10 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref>\n\nMacDonald later returned to Australia and worked as a journalist at ''[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]]'' and then ''[[The Age]]'' in [[Melbourne]], including a stint in the [[Canberra Press Gallery|parliamentary press gallery]]. He was one of the founding members of the [[Australian Journalists Association]] in 1910, spent time in [[London]] and studied at the [[University of London]], before returning to Australia. He was then recruited as editor of the new [[Brisbane]] newspaper ''[[The Daily Standard (Brisbane)|The Daily Standard]]'' in 1912, serving in that role until his appointment to the Senate and also serving as acting manager in 1913-14. He was involved in campaigning against the conscription referendums of [[Billy Hughes]], but in 1918 was one of 12 newspaper editors selected by the [[Nationalist Party (Australia)|Nationalist Party]] government to visit the [[World War I]] front.<ref name=worker /><ref name=bulletin />\n\nOn 26 May 1922, he was appointed to the [[Australian Senate]] as a [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] Senator for Queensland, filling the casual vacancy caused by the death of [[Nationalist Party of Australia|Nationalist]] Senator [[John Adamson (Queensland politician)|John Adamson]]; he had already been preselected as a Labor candidate for the forthcoming election. However, he was defeated at the [[1922 Australian federal election|1922 election]]. MacDonald worked as a freelance journalist in the intervening years. Following the death of another Nationalist Senator, [[Thomas Givens]], MacDonald was again appointed to the Senate on 1 August 1928 but was defeated again at the [[1928 Australian federal election|1928 election]]. He then worked as chief compiler for the Queensland Tourist Bureau, promoting the state's tourist opportunities. MacDonald was finally elected in his own right in the [[1931 Australian federal election|election of 1931]], taking his place in the Senate in 1932. He died in office in 1937 after suffering reported \"heart trouble\" and was cremated at [[Mount Thompson Crematorium]].<ref name=\"Psephos\">{{cite web|last=Carr |first=Adam |title=Australian Election Archive |work=Psephos, Adam Carr's Election Archive |url=http://psephos.adam-carr.net/countries/a/australia |year=2008 |accessdate=2008-11-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5QSilacl0?url=http://psephos.adam-carr.net/countries/a/australia |archivedate=20 July 2007 }}</ref><ref name=worker /><ref name=bulletin /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article70640723 |title=SENATOR J. V. MacDONALD DEAD |newspaper=[[The Central Queensland Herald]] |volume=9 |issue=400 |location=Queensland, Australia |date=19 August 1937 |accessdate=1 September 2019 |page=26 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article178928792 |title=J. V. MacDonald. |newspaper=[[Daily Standard]] |issue=5928 |location=Queensland, Australia |date=15 January 1932 |accessdate=1 September 2019 |page=6 |via=National Library of Australia}} </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Australia-Labor-senator-stub}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Macdonald, John}}\n[[Category:Australian Labor Party members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate for Queensland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian Senate]]\n[[Category:1880 births]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian politicians]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1903-04 \u2192 1903\u201304 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_MacDonald_(Australian_politician)"}
{"title_page": "Andersen", "text_new": "'''Andersen''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8\u0251n\u0250sn\u0329}}) is a [[Denmark|Danish]]-[[Norway|Norwegian]] [[patronymic]] [[surname]] meaning \"son of Anders\" (itself derived from the Greek name \"[[Andreas|\u0391\u03bd\u03b4\u03c1\u03ad\u03b1\u03c2/Andreas]]\", cf. [[English language|English]] [[Andrew]]). It is the fifth most common [[surname]] in [[Denmark]], shared by about 3.2% of the population.<ref>[http://www.dst.dk/HomeUK/Statistics/Names/HowMany.aspx How many have the name \u2013 Statistics Denmark] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100304141125/http://www.dst.dk/HomeUK/Statistics/Names/HowMany.aspx |date=March 4, 2010 }}</ref> \n\nFrom the same root&nbsp;\u2013 the given name ''Andreas''&nbsp;\u2013 derives the [[surname]] '''[[Andresen|Andreasen]]''' {{IPA-da|\u00e6n\u02c8t\u0281e\u02c0\u00e6sn\u0329}} (cognate '''[[Andreassen]]''') and '''[[Andresen]]''' {{IPA-da|\u00e6n\u02c8t\u0281e\u02c0sn\u0329}}.\n\nThe numbers of bearers of the surnames Andersen, Andreasen, Andreassen and Andresen in [[Denmark]] and [[Norway]] (2009):\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!\n!Andersen\n!Andreasen\n!Andreassen\n!Andresen\n!source\n|-\n|Denmark\n|align=\"right\"|165,871\n|align=\"right\"|12,013\n|align=\"right\"|2,430\n|align=\"right\"|4,508\n|[http://www.dst.dk/Statistik/Navne/HvorMange.aspx Statistics Denmark]\n|-\n|Norway\n|align=\"right\"|38,433\n|align=\"right\"|103\n|align=\"right\"|12,376\n|align=\"right\"|6,581\n|[http://www.ssb.no/navn/ Statistics Norway]\n|}\n\n==Persons with the name Andersen==\n* [[Aksel Andersen]] (1912\u20131977), American-Danish organist and composer\n* [[Aksel Frederik Andersen]] (1891\u20131972), Danish mathematician\n* [[Alex H\u00f8gh Andersen]] (born 1994), Danish actor\n* [[Alf Andersen]] (1906\u20131975), Norwegian ski jumper\n* [[Alf Andersen (1928\u20131962)]], Norwegian flautist\n* [[Andr\u00e9 Andersen]] (born 1961), Russian-Danish multi-instrumentalist and composer\n* [[Anja Andersen]] (born 1969), Danish handball coach and former handball player.\n* [[Arthur E. Andersen]] (1885\u20131947), founder of the eponymous former auditing, tax and consulting firm\n* [[Arvid Andersen]] (1909\u20131970), Danish composer\n* [[Benny Andersen]] (1929\u20132018), Danish composer\n* [[Bridgette Andersen]] (1975\u20131997), American child actress\n* [[B\u00f8rge Andersen (chess player)|B\u00f8rge Andersen]] (1934\u20131993), Danish chess player\n* [[Carl Albert Andersen]] (1876-1951), Norwegian pole vaulter\n* [[Chris Andersen]] (born 1978), American basketball player\n* [[Daniel Andersen]] (1885\u20131959), Danish composer\n* [[David Andersen]] (born 1980), Australian basketball player\n* [[Derek Andersen (DJ)|Derek Andersen]], American DJ\n* [[Elisabeth Andersen]] (1920\u20132018), stage name for the Dutch actress Anna Elisabeth de Bruijn\n* [[Erik Andersen (disambiguation)]], several people\n* [[Eyvin Andersen]] (1914\u20131968), Danish composer\n* [[Francis Andersen]] (born 1925), Australian Bible scholar\n* [[Frederik Andersen]] (born 1989), Danish ice hockey goaltender\n* [[Fritz Andersen]] (1829\u20131910), Danish composer\n* [[Hakon Andersen]] (1875\u20131959), Danish composer\n* [[Hans Christian Andersen]] (1805\u20131875), Danish playwright and author\n* [[Hans Niels Andersen]] (1852\u20131937), Danish shipping magnate, businessman and founder of the East Asiatic Company\n* [[Hjalmar Andersen]] (1923\u20132013), Norwegian speed skater\n* [[Joachim Andersen]] (1847\u20131909), Danish flutist, conductor and composer\n* [[Johannes Andersen (musician)]] (1890\u20131980), Danish composer\n* [[Kai Normann Andersen]] (1900\u20131967), Danish composer\n* Kenneth Andersen, Norwegian player of American football and a member of the [[Eidsvoll 1814s]]\n* [[Kim Andersen (cyclist)]] (born 1958), Danish former professional road bicycle racer and current cycling team directeur sportif\n* [[Kirsti Andersen]] (born 1941), historian\n* [[Knud Andersen (disambiguation)]], several people\n* [[LaDell Andersen]] (1929\u20132019), American basketball coach\n* [[Mads Andersen (chess player)|Mads Andersen]] (born 1995), Danish chess grandmaster\n*[[Matt Andersen]], Canadian musician\n* [[May Andersen]] (born 1982), Danish model\n* [[Mikkel Andersen]] (born 1988), Danish footballer\n* [[Morten Andersen]] (born 1960), Danish American football player (field goal kicker and extra points)\n* [[Neil L. Andersen]] (born 1951), member of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles in the LDS Church\n* [[Ron Andersen]] (1941\u20131997), American bridge player\n* [[Roy Andersen]] (born 1955), Norwegian long-distance runner\n* [[Roy Andersen (South Africa)]] (born 1948), South African businessman and military officer\n* [[Sarah Andersen]], American cartoonist (''Sarah's Scribbles'')\n* [[Sophus Andersen]] (1859\u20131923), Danish composer\n* [[Stell Andersen]], (1897\u20131989), American pianist\n* [[Stephan Andersen]] (born 1981), Danish football goalkeeper\n* [[Stephen O. Andersen]] (born 1948), scientist\n* [[Torben Andersen]], American economist\n* [[Uell Stanley Andersen]] (1917\u20131986), American writer\n* [[Vilhelm Andersen]] (1864\u20131953), Danish author\n* [[Ginny Andersen|Virginia Andersen]]''',''' New Zealand politician\n\n==Places==\n===United States Air Force Base===\n* [[Andersen Air Force Base]], Guam\n\n==Companies==\n* [[Andersen Corporation]], a manufacturer of windows and other building supplies\n* [[Arthur Andersen]], a former tax and consulting firm\n* [[Andersen Consulting]], former name of Accenture, Plc\n* [[Pea Soup Andersen's]], a restaurant chain in California\n\n==Medicine==\n* [[Andersen disease]]\n\n==Fiction==\n* [[Jesse Anderson (Yu-Gi-Oh! GX)|Jesse Andersen]], character from the anime ''Yu-Gi-Oh! GX''\n* Riley Andersen, character from Disney Pixar's ''Inside Out''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* {{lookfrom}}\n* {{intitle}}\n* [[Anderson (surname)]]\n* [[Andersson (surname)]]\n* [[Andresen]] (disambiguation)\n\n{{surname}}\n\n[[Category:Danish-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Norwegian-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Patronymic surnames]]\n", "text_old": "'''Andersen''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8\u0251n\u0250sn\u0329}}) is a [[Denmark|Danish]]-[[Norway|Norwegian]] [[patronymic]] [[surname]] meaning \"son of Anders\" (itself derived from the Greek name \"[[Andreas|\u0391\u03bd\u03b4\u03c1\u03ad\u03b1\u03c2/Andreas]]\", cf. [[English language|English]] [[Andrew]]). It is the fifth most common [[surname]] in [[Denmark]], shared by about 3.2% of the population.<ref>[http://www.dst.dk/HomeUK/Statistics/Names/HowMany.aspx How many have the name \u2013 Statistics Denmark] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100304141125/http://www.dst.dk/HomeUK/Statistics/Names/HowMany.aspx |date=March 4, 2010 }}</ref> \n\nFrom the same root&nbsp;\u2013 the given name ''Andreas''&nbsp;\u2013 derives the [[surname]] '''[[Andresen|Andreasen]]''' {{IPA-da|\u00e6n\u02c8t\u0281e\u02c0\u00e6sn\u0329}} (cognate '''[[Andreassen]]''') and '''[[Andresen]]''' {{IPA-da|\u00e6n\u02c8t\u0281e\u02c0sn\u0329}}.\n\nThe numbers of bearers of the surnames Andersen, Andreasen, Andreassen and Andresen in [[Denmark]] and [[Norway]] (2009):\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!\n!Andersen\n!Andreasen\n!Andreassen\n!Andresen\n!source\n|-\n|Denmark\n|align=\"right\"|165,871\n|align=\"right\"|12,013\n|align=\"right\"|2,430\n|align=\"right\"|4,508\n|[http://www.dst.dk/Statistik/Navne/HvorMange.aspx Statistics Denmark]\n|-\n|Norway\n|align=\"right\"|38,433\n|align=\"right\"|103\n|align=\"right\"|12,376\n|align=\"right\"|6,581\n|[http://www.ssb.no/navn/ Statistics Norway]\n|}\n\n==Persons with the name Andersen==\n* [[Aksel Andersen]] (1912\u20131977), American-Danish organist and composer\n* [[Aksel Frederik Andersen]] (1891\u20131972), Danish mathematician\n* [[Alex H\u00f8gh Andersen]] (born 1994), Danish actor\n* [[Alf Andersen]] (1906\u20131975), Norwegian ski jumper\n* [[Alf Andersen (1928\u20131962)]], Norwegian flautist\n* [[Andr\u00e9 Andersen]] (born 1961), Russian-Danish multi-instrumentalist and composer\n* [[Anja Andersen]] (born 1969), Danish handball coach and former handball player.\n* [[Arthur E. Andersen]] (1885-1947), founder of the eponymous former auditing, tax and consulting firm\n* [[Arvid Andersen]] (1909-1970), Danish composer\n* [[Benny Andersen]] (1929-2018), Danish composer\n* [[Bridgette Andersen]] (1975-1997), American child actress\n* [[B\u00f8rge Andersen (chess player)|B\u00f8rge Andersen]] (1934-1993), Danish chess player\n* [[Carl Albert Andersen]] (1876-1951), Norwegian pole vaulter\n* [[Chris Andersen]] (born 1978), American basketball player\n* [[Daniel Andersen]] (1885-1959), Danish composer\n* [[David Andersen]] (born 1980), Australian basketball player\n* [[Derek Andersen (DJ)|Derek Andersen]], American DJ\n* [[Elisabeth Andersen]] (1920-2018), stage name for the Dutch actress Anna Elisabeth de Bruijn\n* [[Erik Andersen (disambiguation)]], several people\n* [[Eyvin Andersen]] (1914\u20131968), Danish composer\n* [[Francis Andersen]] (born 1925), Australian Bible scholar\n* [[Frederik Andersen]] (born 1989), Danish ice hockey goaltender\n* [[Fritz Andersen]] (1829\u20131910), Danish composer\n* [[Hakon Andersen]] (1875-1959), Danish composer\n* [[Hans Christian Andersen]] (1805-1875), Danish playwright and author\n* [[Hans Niels Andersen]] (1852-1937), Danish shipping magnate, businessman and founder of the East Asiatic Company\n* [[Hjalmar Andersen]] (1923\u20132013), Norwegian speed skater\n* [[Joachim Andersen]] (1847-1909), Danish flutist, conductor and composer\n* [[Johannes Andersen (musician)]], Danish composer\n* [[Kai Normann Andersen]], Danish composer\n* Kenneth Andersen, Norwegian player of American football and a member of the [[Eidsvoll 1814s]]\n* [[Kim Andersen (cyclist)]], Danish former professional road bicycle racer and current cycling team directeur sportif\n* [[Kirsti Andersen]] (born 1941), historian\n* [[Knud Andersen (disambiguation)]], several people\n* [[LaDell Andersen]] (1929-2019), American basketball coach\n* [[Mads Andersen (chess player)|Mads Andersen]] (born 1995), Danish chess grandmaster\n*[[Matt Andersen]], Canadian musician\n* [[May Andersen]] (born 1982), Danish model\n* [[Mikkel Andersen]] (born 1988), Danish footballer\n* [[Morten Andersen]] (born 1960), Danish American football player (field goal kicker and extra points)\n* [[Neil L. Andersen]] (born 1951), member of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles in the LDS Church\n* [[Ron Andersen]] (1941-1997), American bridge player\n* [[Roy Andersen]] (born 1955), Norwegian long-distance runner\n* [[Roy Andersen (South Africa)]] (born 1948), South African businessman and military officer\n* [[Sarah Andersen]], American cartoonist (''Sarah's Scribbles'')\n* [[Sophus Andersen]] (1859-1923), Danish composer\n* [[Stell Andersen]], (1897\u20131989), American pianist\n* [[Stephan Andersen]] (born 1981), Danish football goalkeeper\n* [[Stephen O. Andersen]] (born 1948), scientist\n* [[Torben Andersen]], American economist\n* [[Uell Stanley Andersen]] (1917\u20131986), American writer\n* [[Vilhelm Andersen]] (1864\u20131953), Danish author\n* [[Ginny Andersen|Virginia Andersen]]''',''' New Zealand politician\n\n==Places==\n===United States Air Force Base===\n* [[Andersen Air Force Base]], Guam\n\n==Companies==\n* [[Andersen Corporation]], a manufacturer of windows and other building supplies\n* [[Arthur Andersen]], a former tax and consulting firm\n* [[Andersen Consulting]], former name of Accenture, Plc\n* [[Pea Soup Andersen's]], a restaurant chain in California\n\n==Medicine==\n* [[Andersen disease]]\n\n==Fiction==\n* [[Jesse Anderson (Yu-Gi-Oh! GX)|Jesse Andersen]], character from the anime ''Yu-Gi-Oh! GX''\n* Riley Andersen, character from Disney Pixar's ''Inside Out''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* {{lookfrom}}\n* {{intitle}}\n* [[Anderson (surname)]]\n* [[Andersson (surname)]]\n* [[Andresen]] (disambiguatio