Diana Moran]], known as the Green Goddess when she presented keep fit sessions on ''[[BBC Breakfast Time]]'' during the 1980s, is to make a return to breakfast television to give fitness advice to people in self-isolation because of the coronavirus pandemic. She will present a slot on ''[[BBC Breakfast]]'' three times a week.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51933762 |title=Coronavirus: How to exercise while staying at home |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|'''20'''\n|The BBC brings forward [[Malory Towers (TV series)|its adaptation]] of [[Enid Blyton]]'s ''[[Malory Towers]]'' series by two weeks, making it available on BBC iPlayer from Monday 23 March. The series is also scheduled to begin airing on the [[CBBC (TV channel)|CBBC channel]] from April.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tara Conlan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/mar/20/downton-for-kids-bbc-brings-forward-malory-towers-adaptation |title='Downton for kids': BBC brings forward Malory Towers adaptation |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|Filming on the scripted reality television show ''[[The Only Way is Essex]]'' is suspended temporarily because of the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-essex-51976924 |title=Coronavirus: The Only Way is Essex postpones filming |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''22'''\n|ITV announces that filming on ''Coronation Street'' and ''Emmerdale'' will be temporarily halted from Monday 23 March. Its daytime programmes ''[[Lorraine (TV series)|Lorraine]]'' and ''[[Loose Women]]'' will also temporarily cease live broadcasting.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-22/coronavirus-coronation-street-emmerdale-suspend-production-coronavirus-fears/ |title=Lorraine and Loose Women to stop live broadcasting as Coronation Street and Emmerdale suspend filming |work=ITV News |publisher=ITV |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|'''23'''\n|In a televised address, Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] announces a UK-wide lockdown with immediate effect, to contain the spread of the coronavirus. People can leave their homes only for \"very limited purposes\" \u2013 shopping for basic necessities; for one form of exercise a day; for any medical need; and to travel to and from work when \"absolutely necessary\". A number of other restrictions are imposed, with police given powers to enforce the measures, including the use of fines.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-52000039 |title='You must stay at home' UK public told| publisher=BBC | date=23 March 2010| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52012432 |title=Coronavirus: Strict new curbs on life in UK announced by PM| publisher=BBC | date=23 March 2010| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/23/boris-johnson-orders-uk-lockdown-to-be-enforced-by-police |title=\nBoris Johnson orders UK lockdown to be enforced by police| publisher=The Guardian| date=23 March 2010| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> Overnight viewing figures indicate the address, the first such Prime Ministerial broadcast since that by [[Tony Blair]] at the time of the [[Iraq War]] in 2003, to have been watched by a collective audience of at least 27.1 million viewers, placing it high on the [[list of most watched television broadcasts in the United Kingdom]] with the greatest number since the [[2012 Summer Olympics closing ceremony]] in London.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52018502 |title=Coronavirus: 27.1 million watch PM Boris Johnson's TV address |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=24 March 2020 |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> ITV revises its previous decision and announces that ''Emmerdale'' will now broadcast only three times a week from 30 March.\n|-\n|DisneyLife closes and is replaced by [[Disney+]].\n|-\n|rowspan=2|'''24'''\n|BBC News announces that it is delaying plans to cut 450 news jobs due to the pressure of covering the coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52035875 |title=BBC News suspends 450 job cuts to ensure Covid-19 coverage |publisher=BBC |work=BBC News |date=25 March 2020 |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Disney+]] launches in the UK, featuring ''[[The Mandalorian]]'', ''[[High School Musical: The Series]]'', ''[[Forky Asks a Question]]'' and more. It is also the first streaming service in the UK to feature ''[[The Simpsons]]'' after [[Sky UK|Sky]] and [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] secured a deal to make [[Disney+]] available on [[Sky Q]].\n|-\n|rowspan=4|'''26'''\n|''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'' celebrates its 20th anniversary with a 60-minute episode.<ref>{{cite news|first=Zoe |last=Chamberlain |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/showbiz-tv/behind-scenes-bbc-tv-show-17369697 |title=Behind the scenes of BBC TV show Doctors in Birmingham on 20th anniversary |work=Birmingham Mail |publisher=Trinity Mirror |date=8 December 2019 |accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref> The episode sees the return of [[Julia Parsons]] ([[Diane Keen]]) after eight years.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Jones|first=Alison|date=17 March 2020|title=\"Coming back has been heaven!\" says Diane Keen as Julia returns to Doctors|magazine=[[Inside Soap]]|access-date=18 March 2020|url=https://www.insidesoap.co.uk/interviews/coming-back-has-been-heaven-says-diane-keen-as-julia-returns-to-doctors/}}</ref>\n|-\n|The fifteenth anniversary of ''[[Doctor Who]]''{{'}}s return to television is celebrated by fans across the world with a mass viewing of \"[[Rose (Doctor Who episode)|Rose]]\", the first episode from [[Doctor Who (series 1)|the 2005 series]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/entertainment-arts-52050569/doctor-who-fans-unite-with-an-online-viewing |title=Doctor Who fans unite with an online viewing |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=26 March 2020 |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[BBC Scotland]] soap ''[[River City]]'' announces plans to donate medical props to the [[NHS Scotland|NHS]] to help fight coronavirus. The items include surgical gloves, masks and scrubs that would be used by actors during filming of the series.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-scotland-52050746/coronavirus-bbc-scotland-s-river-city-donates-medical-props-to-nhs? |title=Coronavirus: BBC Scotland\u2019s River City donates medical props to NHS |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=26 March 2020 |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[AJ Pritchard]] announces he is leaving ''[[Strictly Come Dancing]]'' after four years.<ref>{{cite news|last=Daly |first=Helen |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2020-03-26/strictly-come-dancing-aj-pritchard-quit/ |title=AJ Pritchard quits BBC show \u2013 here's why |publisher=Radio Times |date=26 March 2020 |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''29'''\n|The team who designed costumes for the [[His Dark Materials (TV series)|TV adaptation]] of [[Philip Pullman]]'s ''[[His Dark Materials]]'' series establish Helping Dress Medics, an organisation dedicated to manufacturing scrubs for medical staff fighting coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52106111 |title=His Dark Materials costume designers switch to making medical scrubs |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=31 March 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''30'''\n|[[Matt Baker (presenter)|Matt Baker]] signs off as co-presenter of ''[[The One Show]]'' after nine years, doing so from home due to having to self-isolate after a relative tested positive for coronavirus. The BBC says it has no plans to replace him, but will instead draw on the show's existing team to co-present with [[Alex Jones (Welsh presenter)|Alex Jones]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52105061 |title=The One Show will not replace Matt Baker after he leaves |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=31 March 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===April===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n|'''3'''\n|The BBC announces it will offer daily educational programming to help children with schoolwork at home during lockdown beginning on 20 April, describing it as the biggest education push \"in its history\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52149409 |title=BBC offers biggest online education push 'in its history' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=3 April 2020 |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''5'''\n|[[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen Elizabeth II]] makes a [[Addresses to the nation by Elizabeth II|rare televised broadcast to the UK and the wider Commonwealth]], something she has done on only four previous occasions. In the address she thanks people for following the government's social distancing rules and pays tribute to key workers, and says the UK \"will succeed\" in its fight against coronavirus but may have \"more still to endure\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52176222 |title=Coronavirus: Queen tells UK 'we will succeed' in fight |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> The broadcast gains 23.97 million viewers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus: The Queen's message seen by 24 million|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52183327|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''6'''\n|''[[Daily Kitchen]]'', a sister programme of ''[[Saturday Kitchen]]'' begins a two-week run on BBC One, intended as a way of helping people isolated at home to cook a meal using limited food resources.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52132848 |title=Daily Kitchen Live to be broadcast for isolation |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=2 April 2020 |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''10'''\n|The BBC has donated fully working [[ventilator]]s from the set of ''[[Holby City]]'' to London's [[NHS Nightingale Hospital London|NHS Nightingale Hospital]] to help treat patients with coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2020/apr/10/working-ventilators-from-holby-city-set-donated-to-nhs-nightingale |title=Working ventilators from Holby City set donated to NHS Nightingale |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=10 April 2020 |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''23'''\n|BBC One airs ''[[The Big Night In]]'', a first-of-its-kind joint broadcast with [[Children in Need]] and [[Comic Relief]], and featuring an evening of music and entertainment. The broadcast celebrates the acts of kindness, humour and the spirit of hope and resilience that is keeping the nation going during the unprecedented COVID-19 pandemic, with viewers given a chance to donate to a fund helping local charities and projects around the country.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/the-big-night-in |title=charity partners to celebrate the UK\u2019s community spirit and resilience with The Big Night In on BBC One |work=BBC Media Centre |publisher=BBC |date=7 April 2020 |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===May===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|}\n\n===June===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|}\n\n===July===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|}\n\n===August===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|}\n\n===September===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|}\n\n===October===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Event\n|-\n| '''23'''\n| ''[[Hollyoaks]]'' celebrates its 25th anniversary.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/hollyoaks/a28453427/hollyoaks-spoilers-25th-anniversary-plans-octob