{"title_page": "Duncan MacDonald (politician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = \n|name               = Duncan MacDonald\n|honorific-suffix   =  \n|image              = \n|caption            =\n\n| constituency_AM1    = [[Electoral district of Stanley (Queensland)|Stanley]]\n| assembly1           = Queensland Legislative\n| term_start1         = 2 April 1938\n| term_end1           = 29 April 1950\n| predecessor1        = [[Roy Bell (politician)|Roy Bell]]\n| successor1          = Seat abolished\n| alongside1          =\n\n| constituency_AM2    = [[Electoral district of Somerset|Somerset]]\n| assembly12           = Queensland Legislative\n| term_start2         = 29 April 1950\n| term_end2           = 7 March 1953\n| predecessor2        = New seat\n| successor2          = [[Alexander Skinner (politician)|Alexander Skinner]]\n| alongside2          =\n\n|birth_date         = {{Birth date|1885|6|30|df=y}} \n|birth_place        = [[Girvan]], [[Ayrshire]], [[Scotland]]\n|death_date         = {{death date and age|1977|9|28|1885|6|30|df=y}}\n|death_place        = [[Maleny]], [[Queensland]], [[Australia]]\n|restingplace       = \n|birthname          = Duncan MacDonald\n|nationality        = [[Scottish Australian]]\n|party              = [[National Party of Australia \u2013 Queensland|Country Party]]\n|otherparty         = \n|spouse             = Mary Irene Enid Ward (m.1913 d.1961)\n|known_for          = \n| occupation        = [[Pastoral farming|Grazier]]\n| relations         = \n| alma_mater        = [[University of Edinburgh]]\n| religion          = [[Uniting Church]]\n}}\n\n'''Duncan MacDonald''' (30 June 1885 \u2013 28 September 1977) was a member of the [[Queensland Legislative Assembly]].<ref name=qp>{{cite web|title=Former Members|publisher=[[Parliament of Queensland]]|year=2015| url=http://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/members/former/bio?id=2548504386|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nMacDonald was born at [[Girvan]], [[Ayrshire]], Scotland, the son of Thomas Duncan MacDonald Snr and his wife Christina (n\u00e9e McLean). He was educated at the [[Glasgow Academy]] [[University of Edinburgh]] and after arriving in [[Queensland]] in 1908 took up a variety of [[The bush|bush]] related jobs. He became the manager of a sugar plantation and then an inspector with the Bureau of Sugar Experiment stations.<ref name=qp/>\n\nIn his youth, Macdonald was a noted boxer and played first-class rugby union. He was a member of the [[Queensland Club]] and a councilor and steward on the [[Royal National Agricultural and Industrial Association of Queensland|Royal National Association]].\n\nOn 4 June 1913 MacDonald married Mary Irene Enid Ward<ref name=qp/> (died 1961)<ref name=bdm>[https://www.qld.gov.au/law/births-deaths-marriages-and-divorces/family-history-research/ Family history research] &mdash; [[Queensland Government|Queensland Government births, deaths, marriages, and divorces]]. Retrieved 21 April 2016.</ref> and together had one son and two daughters. The son, Peter Macdonald (9 January 1916 \u2013 11 March 1943) was an RAAF Pilot Officer, lost presumed killed in WWII.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article78056598 |title=Vote of Condolence |newspaper=[[Nambour Chronicle And North Coast Advertiser]] |issue=2092 |location=Queensland, Australia |date=21 July 1944 |accessdate=5 February 2019 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tgsoba.twgs.qld.edu.au/app/uploads/MacDonald_Peter.pdf|title=MacDonald, Peter}}</ref> His young widow, Orme Augusta Marsh Macdonald, n\u00e9e Bell (18 May 1914 \u2013 11 February 2008), in 1947 married again to widowed solicitor Hubert Silvers Black (17 January 1906 \u2013 22 October 1985), son of mine manager [[Robert Silvers Black]].\n\nHe died at [[Maleny]] in September 1977.<ref name=qp/>\n\n==Public life==\nMacDonald, representing the [[National Party of Australia \u2013 Queensland|Country Party]], won the seat of [[Electoral district of Stanley (Queensland)|Stanley]] at the [[1938 Queensland state election]]. He held the seat until 1950 when the seat was abolished, then moved to the new seat of [[Electoral district of Somerset|Somerset]] which he held until 1953.<ref name=qp/>\n   \nHe was a long-term member of the [[Shire of Landsborough]] council, being a councilor from 1927\u20131936, 1955\u20131958, and 1961\u20131964. He was also the chairman of the shire in 1955\u20131958.\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-qld}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Roy Bell (politician)|Roy Bell]]}}\n{{s-ttl |title= Member for [[Electoral district of Stanley (Queensland)|Stanley]]|years=1938&ndash;1950}}\n{{s-non|reason=Abolished}}\n{{s-new|seat}}\n{{s-ttl |title= Member for [[Electoral district of Somerset|Somerset]]|years=1950&ndash;1953}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Alexander Skinner (politician)|Alexander Skinner]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:MacDonald, Duncan}}\n[[Category:Members of the Queensland Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1977 deaths]]\n[[Category:National Party of Australia members of the Parliament of Queensland]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = \n|name               = Duncan MacDonald\n|honorific-suffix   =  \n|image              = \n|caption            =\n\n| constituency_AM1    = [[Electoral district of Stanley (Queensland)|Stanley]]\n| assembly1           = Queensland Legislative\n| term_start1         = 2 April 1938\n| term_end1           = 29 April 1950\n| predecessor1        = [[Roy Bell (politician)|Roy Bell]]\n| successor1          = Seat abolished\n| alongside1          =\n\n| constituency_AM2    = [[Electoral district of Somerset|Somerset]]\n| assembly12           = Queensland Legislative\n| term_start2         = 29 April 1950\n| term_end2           = 7 March 1953\n| predecessor2        = New seat\n| successor2          = [[Alexander Skinner (politician)|Alexander Skinner]]\n| alongside2          =\n\n|birth_date         = {{Birth date|1885|6|30|df=y}} \n|birth_place        = [[Girvan]], [[Ayrshire]], [[Scotland]]\n|death_date         = {{death date and age|1977|9|28|1885|6|30|df=y}}\n|death_place        = [[Maleny]], [[Queensland]], [[Australia]]\n|restingplace       = \n|birthname          = Duncan MacDonald\n|nationality        = [[Scottish Australian]]\n|party              = [[National Party of Australia \u2013 Queensland|Country Party]]\n|otherparty         = \n|spouse             = Mary Irene Enid Ward (m.1913 d.1961)\n|known_for          = \n| occupation        = [[Pastoral farming|Grazier]]\n| relations         = \n| alma_mater        = [[University of Edinburgh]]\n| religion          = [[Uniting Church]]\n}}\n\n'''Duncan MacDonald''' (30 June 1885 \u2013 28 September 1977) was a member of the [[Queensland Legislative Assembly]].<ref name=qp>{{cite web|title=Former Members|publisher=[[Parliament of Queensland]]|year=2015| url=http://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/members/former/bio?id=2548504386|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nMacDonald was born at [[Girvan]], [[Ayrshire]], Scotland, the son of Thomas Duncan MacDonald Snr and his wife Christina (n\u00e9e McLean). He was educated at the [[Glasgow Academy]] [[University of Edinburgh]] and after arriving in [[Queensland]] in 1908 took up a variety of [[The bush|bush]] related jobs. He became the manager of a sugar plantation and then an inspector with the Bureau of Sugar Experiment stations.<ref name=qp/>\n\nIn his youth, Macdonald was a noted boxer and played first-class rugby union. He was a member of the [[Queensland Club]] and a councilor and steward on the [[Royal National Agricultural and Industrial Association of Queensland|Royal National Association]].\n\nOn 4 June 1913 MacDonald married Mary Irene Enid Ward<ref name=qp/> (died 1961)<ref name=bdm>[https://www.qld.gov.au/law/births-deaths-marriages-and-divorces/family-history-research/ Family history research] &mdash; [[Queensland Government|Queensland Government births, deaths, marriages, and divorces]]. Retrieved 21 April 2016.</ref> and together had one son and two daughters. The son, Peter Macdonald (9 January 1916 \u2013 11 March 1943) was an RAAF Pilot Officer, lost presumed killed in WWII.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article78056598 |title=Vote of Condolence |newspaper=[[Nambour Chronicle And North Coast Advertiser]] |issue=2092 |location=Queensland, Australia |date=21 July 1944 |accessdate=5 February 2019 |page=4 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tgsoba.twgs.qld.edu.au/app/uploads/MacDonald_Peter.pdf|title=MacDonald, Peter}}</ref> His young widow, Orme Augusta Marsh Macdonald, n\u00e9e Bell (18 May 1914 \u2013 11 February 2008), in 1947 married again to widowed solicitor Hubert Silvers Black (17 January 1906 \u2013 22 October 1985), son of mine manager [[Robert Silvers Black]].\n\nHe died at [[Maleny]] in September 1977.<ref name=qp/>\n\n==Public life==\nMacDonald, representing the [[National Party of Australia \u2013 Queensland|Country Party]], won the seat of [[Electoral district of Stanley (Queensland)|Stanley]] at the [[1938 Queensland state election]]. He held the seat until 1950 when the seat was abolished, then moved to the new seat of [[Electoral district of Somerset|Somerset]] which he held until 1953.<ref name=qp/>\n   \nHe was a long-term member of the [[Shire of Landsborough]] council, being a councilor from 1927-1936, 1955-1958, and 1961-1964. He was also the chairman of the shire in 1955-1958.\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-qld}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Roy Bell (politician)|Roy Bell]]}}\n{{s-ttl |title= Member for [[Electoral district of Stanley (Queensland)|Stanley]]|years=1938&ndash;1950}}\n{{